@node I_Tutorial "IdentifyBB2/Tutorial"
@prev I_History
@next I_Author

               @{FG "highlight"}Tutorial@{FG "Text"}

     This archive includes a programming example for all Identify functions.
     You can find all sources and executables in @{b}IdentifyBB2/Examples/@{ub}.
     However, here is a little tutorial.

     First of all, include in your program 

     @{b}IdentifyBB2/amigaincludes/libraries/Identify.bb2@{ub} 

     or use @{b}IdentifyBB2/amigaincludes/libraries/Identify.res@{ub} resident 
     file. 
     Also use BLITZLIBS:amigalibs.res resident, because some system structs
     are used.

     @{b}IdAlert:@{ub} this function requires an AlertID and a TagList.
              All Alert IDs are covered by exec/alerts.h Amiga include.
              If you want to use this function you have to define some
              pointers to strings which will contain Alert's informations.

              All pointers are optional. Using BB2 you can define a pointer
              to string using the AllocMem_ system call.

              ;Example.1

              ALERTID.l=$8000004

              ; Allocating space for string...
              pointer_name.l=AllocMem_(bytesize,#MEMF_CLEAR)

              ;Now define a taglist...
              ;I supposed to get only the Alert's Specified cause

              Dim Tags.TagItem(2)
              Tags(0)\ti_Tag=#IDTAG_SpecStr,pointer_name
              Tags(1)\ti_Tag=#IDTAG_StrLength,50          ;ByteSize for string
                                                          ;pointed by pointer_name
              Tags(2)\ti_Tag=#TAG_DONE

              ;Call IdAlert_
              Error=IdAlert_(ALERTID,&Tags(0))

              ;If Error=0 then you use the string describing Alert's
              ; specified cause...

              If Error=0
                 NPrint Peek$(pointer_name)
              End If

              FreeMem_(pointer_name)

     @{b}IdFunction:@{ub} this function requires a library name, a function offset
                 (positive) and a TagList.

               ;Defining a string pointer...
               STRPTR.l=AllocMem_(50,#MEMF_CLEAR)

               ;Defining a TagList...
               Dim Tags.TagItem(2)
               Tags(0)\ti_Tag=#IDTAG_FunctionStr,STRPTR
               Tags(1)\ti_Tag=#IDTAG_StrLength,50          ;ByteSize for string
                                                           ;pointed by pointer_name
               Tags(2)\ti_Tag=#TAG_DONE

               ;Call IdFunction_
               Error=IdFunction_("exec.library",30,&Tags(0)) 

               ;If Error=0 you should find OpenLibrary in STRPTR...
               if Error=0 Then NPrint Peek$(STRPTR)

               FreeMem_(STRPTR)

     @{b}IdExpansion:@{ub} Infos for any Zorro I/II/III board mounted on your Amiga.
                  This funcion is very powerful but you need to know well 
                  some Amiga system calls and structs.

                  @{i}Example.3@{ui}
                  
                  ;We want to get the manufactur's name for the first board.
                  ;So, let me allocate space for a string 50 bytes sized.

                  MANUF.l=AllocMem_(50,#MEMF_CLEAR)

                  ;I define a TagList...
                  Dim Tags.TagItem(2)
                  Tags(0)\ti_Tag=#IDTAG_ManufStr,MANUF
                  Tags(1)\ti_Tag=#IDTAG_StrLength,50
                  Tags(2)\ti_Tag=#TAG_DONE

                  ;I define a pointer to a ConfigDev struct..
                  ;getting the first board.
                  ;
                  *Zorro.ConfigDev=FindConfigDev_(0,-1,-1)
                  
                  ;Get manufactur's name...
                  If Zorro
                      Error=IdExpansion_(*Zorro,&Tags(0))
                      If Error=0
                         NPrint Peek$(MANUF) ;Print manufactur's name
                      End If
                  End If

                  FreeMem_(MANUF)

               I tested this function on my A1200 with PhaseV's Blizzard IV
               and it worked well. I used my little utility Expansion (provided)
               that checks all Zorro boards mounted and not only the first. It should
               be work on any Amiga/Draco systems.

     @{b}IdHardware:@{ub} This powerful function returns a string describing any information
                 you want. It can check for Amiga/Draco machine's name, GFX system,
                 total memory mounted and more...

			  @{i}Example.4@{ui}
                 
                 ;Printing machine's type...
                 NPrint Peek$(IdHardware_(#IDHW_SYSTEM,0))
                 
                 ;Cpu
                 NPrint Peek$(IdHardware_(#IDHW_CPU,0))


    @{b}IdHardwareNum:@{ub} Same as IdHardware but it returns a numerical
                            value.

			 @{i}Example.5@{ui}
                 
                 ;Check for 68030 processor
                 If (IdHardwareNum_(#IDHW_CPU,0)=#IDCPU_68030) or
                    (IdHardwareNum_(#IDHW_CPU,0)=#IDCPU_68030EC)
                    ;
                    ; Do your job here...
                    ;
                 End If

    @{b}IdHardwareUpdate:@{ub} used to update the internal identify's
                               structure allocated for config's informations.
                                     

                 
@endnode

